  <static seed="1467" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations28.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{4}{y-7}-\frac{3}{y-8}}={-\frac{2}{y^{2}-15y+56}}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{9\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{\left(y-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-8\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{4}{y-7}-\frac{3}{y-8}} \amp = {-\frac{2}{y^{2}-15y+56}} \\
  {\frac{4}{y-7}-\frac{3}{y-8}} \amp = {-\frac{2}{\left(y-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-8\right)}} \\
  {\frac{4}{y-7}\mathopen{}\left(y-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-8\right)-\frac{3}{y-8}\mathopen{}\left(y-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-8\right)} \amp = {-\frac{2}{\left(y-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-8\right)}\mathopen{}\left(y-7\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-8\right)} \\
  {4\mathopen{}\left(y-8\right)-3\mathopen{}\left(y-7\right)} \amp = {-2} \\
  {4y-32-3y+21} \amp = {-2} \\
  {y-11} \amp = {-2} \\
  {y} \amp = 9 \\
  
  
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p>For this example, it<rsq/>s easy to see we must exclude <m>7</m> and <m>8</m> from the solution set. These values are not in the solution set we got, so the final solution is <m>y=9</m>.</p>
</solution>
